														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-431559">
									

<p>It depends on how effective it is. If its effects are on the level of a three or four, you add a level for intent, so if it's as dangerous (minus intent) as a level 3, intent would bump it up to a four, not a five.</p>
<p>If <em>most</em> of the people who survived were permanently comatose, I'd agree with this being a five. The way it's written, though, it sounds like the after-effects are more like a standard traumatic experience (i.e., getting trapped in a house fire and seeing all your loved ones die, being a victim of long term child abuse, etc.) - there are long-term effects that need continued therapy to treat, and sometimes the trauma is enough to lead to being permanently comatose, but most survivors are still themselves (if badly and, sometimes, permanently shaken), so it's effectively a Level 3. The intent thus brings it to a final Mental Threat Level of 4.</p>

							</div>

								
					
